Business Understanding¶

The purpose of this project is to try and predict if a particular TV show will be either renewed or canceled. This will be based on data collected and analyzed from IMDb and twitter. In particular, I will try to gauge the shows popularity by:

  • looking at the IMDb score and the number of users who voted
  • analyzing sentiment of the reviews
  • analyzing review scores
  • analyzing the shows popularity by it twitter following

If successful, the real world applications of this could be:

  • Help networks decide whether or not to renew or cancel a show
  • Could help entertainment news agencies better predict a shows renewal\cancellation

The question I would like to answer are:

  1. Does a strong twitter following lead to a shows renewal?
  2. Can the shows IMDb score help to predict it's cancellation?
  3. Is there a correlation to the sentiment from the shows reviews and it being renewed\canceled?

Sources¶

The source of the data comes from 3 places, Metacritc, IMDb and Twitter.

The data collected from metacritic includes:

  • TV show name
  • Renewed\Cancel status
  • Network show aired on

The data collected from IMDb includes:

  • Title
  • IMDb Score
  • Number of users voted
  • If applicable, the shows ranking within IMDb top 250 TV shows
  • Keywords
  • Genres
  • Content rating
  • Country
  • Language
  • Release Date
  • Runtime
  • TV Network

The Data Collected from Twitter includes:

  • Name
  • twitter handle (screenname)
  • number of follower

Data Collection Techniques¶

The methods for collecting the data was web crawling and the Twitter API The code for data collection was written in python separate from the Juptyer Notebook and can be found in the GIT repository. See below for a detailed explanation:

The data collection was split into three parts:

  1. Getting the appropriate IMDb links
  2. Getting the appropriate IMDb Data
  3. Getting the appropriate Twitter data

The first step was to scrape the metacritic website to get a list of renewed\canceled TV shows. Once completed, I could use the shows name to build an IMDb query url in order to find all the IMDb Links associated with the show name. There were some issues where the search string wasn't quite right and IMDb resulted in incorrect results. These were very few and were not added to the final list. The code for the link collection can be found in the Get_IMDb_Links folder.

The second step was to collect the IMDb data for each of the links created from the first step. All the data was collected using Beautiful Soup instead of xpath extraction. The code can be found in the Get_IMDb_Data folder.

The last step was to collect the Twitter data. This step turned out to be the most challenging as most of of the shows didn't have an Official Site embeded in its IMDb page. I used the Python package Tweepy to search twitter for users with the query string being the show name. In some cases, I added the network to the query string.

In the case where I did have a link from IMDb to the shows Official Twitter page, I noticed that some of those links were not working. I found out that was due the fact that the tokens have updated thus invalidating the originally collected link from IMDb. Instead of using the links I had already collected, I decided to collect the link at the time of needing it. From there I used Beautiful Soup to scrape the twitter handle and later pushed it through the twitter API to get the information needed.

Since twitter's search users api call returns multiple results, I created a crude algorithm in order to determine the most likely twitter account. For example, the show Zoo shows results from different city zoos. I needed to determine which twitter user was more likely to be the TV show. I did this by implementing a series of checks that look at the Twitter users name, screenname, and description and I check it against the characteristic of the show (network, name, etc). In addition, if the account is verified, I increase the measured weight. This proved to be very accurate with only a few being incorrect, these are still in the dataset.

The code for the Twitter data collection can be found in the Get_social_media_data folder.

In total, there was data collected on 276 TV shows. The breakdown can be seen below:

Renewed TV Shows:

  • Total number of shows: 197
  • Total number of reviews: 12,387
  • Total number of words: 1,878,703

Canceled TV Shows:

  • Total number of shows: 78
  • Total number of reviews: 4,671
  • Total number of words: 715,686

Rescued TV Shows:

  • Total number of shows: 1
  • Total number of reviews: 75
  • Total number of words: 10,135

All the datasets can be found in the Data folder. Each category (renewed\canceled\rescued) has its own 4 datasets. The first one (i.e. canceled.json) contains the IMDB links, TV show name, and Network. The second (i.e. canceled_IMDB_data.json) contains all the collected IMDb data minus the reviews. The third (i.e. canceled_imdb_reviews.json) contains all the imdb review data, and the last file (i.e. canceledTwitterData.json) contains twitter following data.

# function for merging list of dictionaries 
# Modified from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3421906/how-to-merge-lists-of-dictionaries
def merge_lists(l1, l2, key, typeSM):
    merged = {}
    count = 0
    for item in l1+l2:
        if item[key] in merged:
            if typeSM == 'twitter':
                try:
                    twitter = {"twitter_followers":l2[count]['twitter_data']['followers_count'], 'twitter_screenname':l2[count]['twitter_data']['screen_name']}
                    merged[item[key]].update(twitter)
                except:
                    twitter = {"twitter_followers": None, 'twitter_screenname': None}
                    merged[item[key]].update(twitter)
            elif typeSM == 'review':
                if item[key] in merged:
                    merged[item[key]].update(item)
            count += 1
        else:
            merged[item[key]] = item
    
    for (_, val) in merged.items():
        items = val
        try:
            if items['twitter_followers'] or not items['twitter_followers']:
                pass
        except:
            twitter = {"twitter_followers": None, 'twitter_screenname': None}
            #for each in followers:
            merged[items['tv_show_name']].update(twitter)

    return [val for (_, val) in merged.items()]

# Function to return sentiment on passed in list

def vader(r):
    reviews = []
    for i in r:
        reviews.append(i)
    
    positive_review = []
    negative_review = []
    neutral_review = []
    
    analyzer = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
    
    for sentence in reviews:
        vs = analyzer.polarity_scores(sentence)
        #print(("{:-<65} {}".format(sentence, str(vs))))
        if vs['compound'] > 0.8:
            positive_review.append(sentence)
        elif vs['compound'] < 0:
            negative_review.append(sentence)
        else:
            neutral_review.append(sentence)
            
    return len(positive_review), len(negative_review), len(neutral_review)

# This function takes the review data in a dataframe and calculates the average review rating and the avg sentiment for review titles and review text for each show in the df.
def processReviewData(dataframe):
    review_data = []

    for i in range(len(dataframe)):
        # Go through each tv shows diction of imdb_reviews 
        place = dataframe.iloc[i].imdb_reviews
        
        # get the show name, to be used later as the key in merging
        tv_show_name = dataframe.iloc[i].tv_show_name

        scores = []
        Reviews = []
        ReviewTitle = []

        for n in range(len(dataframe.iloc[i].imdb_reviews)):
            # go through each element in the show's review dictionary and get all the score, titles and review 
            #text to be stored in a list
            
            if place[n]['review_score'] is not None:
                scores.append(int(place[n]['review_score']))
            
            if place[n]['review_title'] is not "":
                ReviewTitle.append(place[n]['review_title'])
            
            if place[n]['review_text'] is not None:
                Reviews.append(place[n]['review_text'])
                
        try:
            avg_score = round(sum(scores)/len(scores), 1)
        except:
            avg_score = None

        try:
            reviews_vaderSent = vader(list(Reviews))
        except:
            reviews_vaderSent = [None, None, None]
            
        try:
            revTitle_vaderSent = vader(list(ReviewTitle))
        except:
            revTitle_vaderSent = [None, None, None]

        review_data.append({
            'tv_show_name': tv_show_name,
            'avg_review_score': avg_score,
            'pos_review_sent': reviews_vaderSent[0],
            'neg_review_sent': reviews_vaderSent[1],
            'neut_review_sent': reviews_vaderSent[2],
            'pos_revTitle_sent': revTitle_vaderSent[0],
            'neg_revTitle_sent': revTitle_vaderSent[1],
            'neut_revTitle_sent': revTitle_vaderSent[2],
        })
        
    return review_data

# Remove Official sites link from list as it is not needed.

renewedIMDbData = [{k: v for k, v in d.items() if k != 'official_sites'} for d in renewedIMDbData]
canceledIMDbData = [{k: v for k, v in d.items() if k != 'official_sites'} for d in canceledIMDbData]

# This function extracts all the review texts from the list of dictionaries
def returnText(data, typeText):
    reviewText = []
    
    if typeText == "review":
        searchFor = 'review_text'
    elif typeText == "title":
        searchFor = 'review_title'
    else:
        return "Error: Only 'review' or 'title' are valid inputs for typeText"
    
    for i in range(len(data)):
        reviewData = data[i]['imdb_reviews']
        
        for n in range(len(reviewData)):
            reviewText.append(str(reviewData[n][searchFor]))
    
    return reviewText

# function to return words counts for each review 
def returnWordCount(data):
    
    word_count = []
    
    for i in range(len(data)):
        word_count.append(len(data[i].split()))
    
    return word_count

# Function to place 1000s seperator within a given number.
def place_value(num):
    return ("{:,}".format(num))

# This is a function for data cleaning
def text_processing(review):
    # what if you have additional stopwords to be removed
    tokens = str(review)
    
    #lowecases
    tokens = tokens.lower()
    
    # Remove useless numbers and alphanumerical words
    tokens = re.sub("[^a-zA-Z0-9]", " ", tokens)
    
    #tokenization or word split
    tokens = word_tokenize(tokens)
    
    #get stemming words or lemmas
    wordnet_lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    tokens = (wordnet_lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in tokens)
    
    #additional stopwrods
    more_stopwords = set(('show', 'character', 'episode', 'series', 'really', 'get', 'first', 'people', 'also', 'two', 'season', 'one'))
    extra_stoplist = set(stopwords.words('english')) | more_stopwords
    tokens = (word for word in tokens if word not in extra_stoplist)
    
    # Filter non-alphanumeric characters from tokens
    tokens = (word for word in tokens if word.isalpha())
    
    #remove short words
    tokens = (word for word in tokens if len(word) > 3)
    
    return tokens

# I was not able to do subplots using fdist.plot(). Thus, the method below breaks apart the x and y values (word, freq) of the distribution and plots them.
# This idea was modified from section 10.3 from the following source: http://www.tulane.edu/~howard/NLP/textstats.html

ldata = [rTxtDist, rTitleDist, cTxtDist, cTitleDist]
titles = ['Renewed TV shows: Popular words in review text', 'Renewed TV shows: Top words in review titles', 'Canceled TV shows: Top words in review text', 'Canceled TV shows: Top words in review titles']

limit = 30
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 20))

for (pane, test) in enumerate(ldata):
    if pane == 0: 
        XY = rTxtDist.items()
    elif pane == 1:
        XY = rTitleDist.items()
    elif pane == 2:
        XY = cTxtDist.items()
    elif pane == 3:
        XY = cTitleDist.items()
    
        
    XY = sorted(XY, key=lambda pair: pair[1], reverse=True)
    XY.sort(key=lambda pair: pair[1], reverse=True)

    X = [x for (x,y) in XY[:limit]]
    Y = [y for (x,y) in XY[:limit]]

    nX = range(len(X))
    
    plt.subplot(4, 2, pane+1)
    plt.plot(nX, Y, label='counts to tokens')
    plt.xticks(nX, X, rotation='vertical', fontsize='14')
    plt.yticks(fontsize='14')
    
    if pane == 0: plt.ylabel('Counts', fontsize='14')
    elif pane %2 == 0:
        #plt.xlabel('Tokens', fontsize='14')
        plt.ylabel('Counts', fontsize='14')

    plt.title(titles[pane], fontsize='16')
    plt.grid()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The review title are actually a bit more telling and show the intent a bit better. However, what I find interesting is that the popular words when compared to renewed and canceled review text\titles is very similar.

Renewed TV show review titles, however, do have more positive and descriptive adjectives. Words good, great, love, best, funny are shared between both renewed and canceled review titles, however, renewed review titles have words like hilarious, brilliant, awesome, excellent, and entertaining.

Word Clouds¶

Helper Functions¶
In [33]:
# This is a function to generate a wordcloud. I made it so I wouldn't have to copy and paste the code evertime I wanted to make a new worldcloudabs.

def gen_wordcloud(data, w, h, type_dist, words= None, title = None):
    """This function is used to generate a Word Cloud from frequency dictionary.
    
    Parameters: 
    data (dict): This is a dictionary that contains the word as a key and count as a value
    
    w (float): Width of the figure
    
    h (float): Height of the figure
    
    type_dist (string): The type of data that is passed in . Must be 'f' for frequency distribution and 'b' for bigrams. Anything else throws an error.
    
    words (list): A list of words to be removed from the passed in dictionary. This is optional.
    
    title (string): The title of the Word Cloud. This is optional.
    
    """
    
    if type_dist == "f":
        # Copy the passed in freq dict so that we don't change it if stopwords are passed in.
        tempDict = dict(data)
        
        # If stopwords are passed into function, remove them from the temporary dictionary
        if words:
        
            # If word is 4 characters or less, add it to the stopwords list
            words.extend(stopwords.words('english'))
            words.extend(word for word in data.keys() if len(word) <= 4)

            for i in words:
                if i in tempDict.keys():
                    tempDict.pop(i, None)
                    
    elif type_dist== "b":
        copyDict = dict(data)
        tempDict = defaultdict(int)
        
        if words:
            words.extend(stopwords.words('english'))
            #words.extend(word[0] for word in copyDict.keys() if len(word[0]) <= 4)
            #words.extend(word[1] for word in copyDict.keys() if len(word[1]) <= 4)
            for i in words:
                for n in list(copyDict.keys()):
                    if (i == n[0]) | (i == n[1]):
                        copyDict.pop((n))
                        
        for i in list(copyDict.keys()):
            tempDict['_'.join(i)] = copyDict[i]
    else: 
        print("Error: did not provide correct type")
        return
                    
    # Set up word cloud settings and generate from frequencies
    wordcloud = WordCloud(
        background_color='white', 
        max_words=250, 
        width=1920,
        height=1080,
        ).generate_from_frequencies(tempDict)
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(w, h), dpi=150)
    plt.axis("off")
    
    # Set title if passed into function
    if title:
        plt.title(title, fontsize=12)
        
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.show()

Results¶

The only show that was rescued (as collected by web scraping) was Brooklyn Nine-Nine. We can see that just that one single show has a twitter following of 607,308 people was ranked in the IMDb's Top 250 best tv shows. There were only two other canceled shows that made that list, 'Ash vs Evil Dead' and 'The Expanse'. Both of those shows have very high IMDb and review scores, however, only one of those shows, 'The Expanse', has a high positive sentiment on its reviews. A quick Google search actually shows that 'The Expanse' was rescued recently as well.

When looking at the average sentiment across all shows that were canceled, we can see that the average positive sentiment is considerably lower than that of Brooklyn Nine-Nine, 53.85% compared to 74.67% and higher on the negative sentiment side, 26.81% compared to 12%.

Content Analysis¶

I decided to try and do text classification on the review text for both renewed and canceled tv shows to see if we can try to predict renewal\cancellation from the review text found in IMDB. To do this I need to combine the to datasets and assign them a classification. I will assign a 1 to renewed shows and a 0 for canceled shows. For this analysis, I will be ignoring the rescued dataset.

Summary of Classification Models¶

Out of curiosity, I wanted to see the difference in using text from reviews vs the text from review titles to see which would be a better model. The model built from review text was 82.5% accurate while the model built from review titles was 61.3% accurate.

The confusion matrix from the Naive Bayes Model shows that 713 reviews were correctly classified as renewed shows while 181 were false negatives meaning some shows were classified incorrectly as renewed by were in face canceled. There were also 125 false positives.

The grid search did give us a slightly better accuracy from 82.5% to 83.6%.

I also ran the KNN and the SVM models and found that the Naive Bayes Model was the best with the SVM model close behind with an accuracy of 79.3% vs 83.6% from the NB model.

Model Deployment¶

For the model deployment, I decided I wanted to scrape new data. The original list of shows that were canceled\renewed were from the 2017-2018 season. I decided to pull the reviews from one renewed show and one canceled show. The renewed show was Bosch from Amazom Prime and the canceled show was Santa Clarita Diet from Netflix.

As I did before, I will pull 75 reviews from IMDB for each show and run both lists of reviews through the Naive Bayes model.

I am interested to find out what the prediction will be for Santa Clarita Diet. There has been a huge outry from fans that really enjoy this show. Popular social media sites like Twitter and Reddit show that a large amount of people are unhappy with Netflix's decision to cancel the show which could lead to subscription cancellation for Netflix.

from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import urllib3

def load_url(url):
    http = urllib3.PoolManager()
    fp = http.request('GET', url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(fp.data, features='lxml')
    
    return soup

def getReviewText(link):
    imdbRevs = []
    
    movieID = re.search(r"(tt[0-9]{7})", link).group()
    baseUrl = "https://www.imdb.com/title/%s/reviews/_ajax" %(movieID)
    paginationUrl = "?ref_=undefined&paginationKey="    

    reviewsSoup = load_url(baseUrl)

    # get next
    for i in range(3):    
        try:
            paginationKey = reviewsSoup.find('div', {'class':'load-more-data'})['data-key']
        except:
            paginationKey = None
            pass

        for data in reviewsSoup.findAll('div', {'class':'lister-item'}):

            try:
                revText = data.find('div', {'class':'text'}).text.strip()
            except:
                revText = None

            imdbRevs.append(revText)

            if paginationKey is not None:
                newUrl = baseUrl + paginationUrl + paginationKey
                reviewsSoup = load_url(newUrl)
            else:
                pass
        
    return imdbRevs

Story Telling¶

Insights:¶

  • ABC, Netflix, NBC, CBS, and Fox have the most canceled shows
  • Netflix has the most renewals, followed by ABC, NBC, Fox, and HBO
  • Not counting the outliers, ABC has the highest twitter following with headliners like Grey's Anatomy, American Idol and How to Get Away with Murder.
  • Shows that have a higher twitter following has a higher chance of renewal.
  • There is high positive sentiment for canceled shows. This is possibly upsetting to fans of the canceled shows.

Implications¶

Since TV networks have limited time to air shows and gain customers, they not only need to produce excellent content to keep consumers coming back, but they also need to know when to renew or cancel a show. There have been many instances where a show was canceled and followed by an large public outcry. Take the show Brooklyn Nine-Nine for example, originally it was aired on FOX. After the fifth season, FOX canceled the show and there was a huge public outcry on reddit and Twitter. The day of the cancellation, the #RenewB99 hashtag was trending and the very next day the show was picked up by NBC.

Santa Clarita Diet is in the same boat. Netflix recently canceled the show which resulted in backlash from fans. The decision to cancel a show can have huge consequences for a network.

Possible Improvements¶

One possible improvement is to dive deeper into canceled shows to find those that may have a large fanbase that would be unhappy with a networks decision to cancel. I would love to then analyze the response to a shows cancellation announcement on twitter.

Another improvement could be to look into a network analysis of popular shows. It would be interesting to see how many people with a high twitter following like a specific show. A good example is a tweet from Lin-Manual Miranda calling for Brooklyn Nine-Nine to be renewed. That tweet was retweeted 76,000 times and liked 215,688.
